{{Refimprove|date=December 2017}}
'''Chatterton’s compound''' was an adhesive waterproof [[Electrical insulation|insulating compound]] that was used in early [[submarine telegraph cable]]s.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=fyCqJ8-BBMAC&pg=PA58 "Submarine Telegraphs: Their History, Construction, and Working, Bright 1898"]</ref> It was patented in 1859 by John Chatterton and Willoughby Smith.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=CwcLAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA198 "The Repertory of Patent Inventions: And Other Discoveries and Improvements"]</ref>
Its constitution is as follows: *3 parts [[gutta-percha]] *1 part [[rosin]] *1 part [[pine tar|Stockholm tar]]
Chatterton's Compound was also used to stick insulating paper to armatures, for example those on [[Shortt-Synchronome clock|Synchronome]] clocks, which were the most accurate clocks made in the early part of the 20th century. If the paper appeared to be in bad condition it could be removed by warming up the armature near a flame and replacing it.
Chatterton's Compound was used in the manufacture of pneumatic pipe organs to seal lead tubing into wooden blocks for the pneumatic action, or, particularly in the UK, to affix reed weights to the reed tongues. It is still used in historical restoration jobs for this purpose but has been replaced with modern materials on more recent builds.
Chatterton's Compound was much used by submarine cable technicians for various purposes around oversea telegraph offices prior to the 1960s; it could be used as an adhesive or in jointing gutta-percha-insulated submarine telegraph cables. It was available in round black sticks of about 3/4&nbsp;inch diameter which responded to heat from a [[alcohol burner|spirit lamp]]. It was known to telegraph technicians as 'chats'.
In France, the normal black PVC [[Electrical tape|electrical insulating tape]] is often referred to as ''chatterton''.
